metadata.name: The Past Ahead #194
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

metadata.name: Attractor #235
metadata.description:
People are often drawn together over shared interest, and through their connections to those interests they find connections with others. Attractor is a visualization of community, a central interest bringing people together, pushing past their walls, bad habits, and traumas. The image is meant to be deceiving in its focus on the attractor, where the true focus is on the overlaps and complex defenses we build around ourselves. Those defenses can make us and those connections into more beautiful, ornate structures, or keep us distant from those around us. Sometimes focusing on a shared attractor is the only way we can let down our guard.

Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle the grain for printing or personal preference
Press ‘p’ to save a higher quality .png
Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: an abstract concept #13
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.

metadata.name: sketch: cairn() #43
metadata.description:
A cairn is a monument made of stacked rocks. In modern times, often used for wayfinding in remote areas, as in mountaineering, or to indicate an area of significance.

In this sketch I imagine these monuments -- through the looking glass. Paying mind to the simplicity of their construction, as well as the mysticism of what each might represent.

---

Sketch is a series meant to celebrate learning and experimentation.

In this sketch I experiment with subdivision, smoothing, textures, multiple levels of domain warping, and illustration techniques.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press s to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at size

metadata.name: Tomorrow #177
metadata.description:
Tomorrow is probably the biggest uncertainty of our lives.

We hang absolutely everything on tomorrow, the beginning of a new life, training, studies, hopes, expectations, dreams, and many other things, the list can be very long.

But how often do our expectations come true?

This year I hope everyone understood that you cannot hope and count on tomorrow, there is no tomorrow, there is only today.
Stop putting everything off until tomorrow, you may just not notice how your life flew by and you ended up not doing so much.

The shape of the circle was not chosen by chance, it represents the cyclical nature of our lives and everything we do.
But even in this there are exceptions, expecting that tomorrow everything will go on the same scenario, everything goes exactly the opposite.

15 palettes.
5 formats.
2 different drawing modes.

Press S for Save Canvas as PNG.

By aleks.ustya, @ALEKUSTN. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Wiz Punks #60
metadata.description:
When cybernetic meets elder magic, the result is a society where limits are rare and free will must come with a very loaded moral sense to avoid turning inofensive particles into mass destruction spells or even virtual cults that invades ordinary meditation.
In the Wiz Punks universe, these 1000 characters are living in the chaotic Fantastic City, where technology must be balanced with the ancient and the rules are under the sight of the Bench, farmers use magic to animate food and go to battle. Religious people use body modification to cult their gods, while gangs try to hack ultra security libraries and bread it's made with magic. 
If you feel ready to live into the chaos where your brain can be hacked anytime, but also where you could use spells to manipulate elements, you are a Wiz Punks.

metadata.name: Skyward Theatre #12
metadata.description:
“So the sky became the most enchanting canvas of all, limitless in its potential. What was painted there would be beautiful, if only for a moment”

---

Gen art relies on the randomness of the universe to fill artistic systems with life. So it is with a fireworks display. There is a plan, arrangement, and sequence. But the system only comes alive when it leaves the realm of order and control. Skyward Theatre is a tribute to this analog generative technique.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press p to pause
- Press s to save png

metadata.name: The Likeness of a Flower #105
metadata.description:
And the unseen eyebeam crossed, for the roses
Had the look of flowers that are looked at.
- T.S. Eliot, Four Quartets: Burnt Norton (1936)

This work is an attempt to encapsulate in an algorithm, not the likeness of a flower, but the likeness of a painting of a flower. If, according to a very old definition, art is an imitation of nature, this is an imitation of an imitation – a sort of meta-imitation of nature by means of computer code.

The challenge for this piece was to capture some of the looseness and fluidity of the human hand when holding a brush or a pencil, and reproducing some typical forms of hand-made scribbles, doodles and brush strokes. However, absent the materiality of paint and canvas, everything is simulated here on the base of a very simple resource: circles. Everything you see is built of very many overlapping circles of varying sizes, colors and opacities. It is circles all the way down…

Inspiration for this work comes from a number of expressionist painters, from 20th century classics like Cy Twombly, to the magnificent contemporary work of Philip Maltman: https://www.instagram.com/philipmaltman/

This work is animated.
Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 1000 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

Made with the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Expresión Urbanistica #45
metadata.description:
"Expresión Urbanistica" is a collection inspired by urban textures and development. The original idea came from the landscape of my city which is vibrant and sometimes soft in terms of color. 

For me "Expresión Urbanistica" is the feeling that I get each time that I look through my window, each time that I get out of my house, and each time I watch a sunset through my balcony.

metadata.name: Staccato #95
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Containing just three basic repeating shapes, 'Staccato' is inspired by minimalist geometric art.
Each 'Staccato' output forms a bold, colorful and (hopefully) pleasing design.

In live mode:
